WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.840
It's also very important to the ethos of the work

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:06.720
that we do at Black Sky.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:09.230
And I love this quote because as someone who studies race in

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:11.600
the internet, a lot of times they will try to make

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:14.360
you choose what issue is the most important issue when it comes

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:16.900
to trust and safety, but there is no single issue when

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:21.550
we're dealing with marginalized identities that overlap.

00:00:21.800 --> 00:00:24.310
So like I said, for the past 12 plus years,

00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:26.600
I've been doing research about this.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:30.720
I've talked to black women and non-binary people across

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:32.520
the black diaspora.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:35.320
And this is directly from the research that I did with interviewing

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:35.720
them.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:39.050
And when I was doing this work, I was always dreaming

00:00:39.050 --> 00:00:42.820
of being able to work with a company or an organization that

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:46.950
was actually trying to mitigate harm against black women and non-

00:00:46.950 --> 00:00:51.100
binary gender expansive people specifically, but also anti-blackness

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:51.360
.

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:54.160
And this was like my driving force, but I didn't

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:56.480
know if anything existed like that.

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:58.820
So when I decided to make my Blue Sky account, one

00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:01.800
of my really good friends told me about Black Sky.

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:03.260
And I was like, "Hmm, what's that?"

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:05.030
So I slid in Rudy's DMs and I said

00:01:05.030 --> 00:01:07.390
, "Hey, we need to meet." And from then

00:01:07.390 --> 00:01:09.100
I became a volunteer moderator.

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:11.990
And one of the things that I really wanted to focus on

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:14.560
doing my work as a moderator, because I came from a

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:17.770
research background, was taking the research that I had used,

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.930
the reading that I had done, and using that to help

00:01:20.990 --> 00:01:25.230
implement trust and safety for our moderation tool, which is what

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:27.000
I'll be talking about today.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.800
So when I first started, there was a very, very

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:32.790
, very small team of moderators, Rudy being one of

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:33.440
them.

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:36.280
And this is what the original page looked like.

00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:37.380
We had two labels.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:40.240
It was misogynoir and anti-black harassment.

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:43.620
And this is our beautiful team that has grown over the past

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:44.460
year or so.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:48.000
And I'm saying here that the beginning matters because there was

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:51.470
a need for this type of moderation tool and tech in general

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:55.720
, but being in a decentralized space allowed us to actually create

00:01:55.860 --> 00:02:01.160
said tool and have control over how we can moderate these spaces

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.200
to make people safe.

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:06.000
So who puts the trust in trust and safety, right?

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:08.470
One of the big things that I talk a lot about in

00:02:08.470 --> 00:02:11.410
my work and really drives the work that we do is that

00:02:11.410 --> 00:02:14.320
if you don't have community trust, then you don't

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:18.280
have a very good trust and safety situation going on.

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:19.280
And that's just the reality.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:21.490
Because when you think about trust and safety, the trust is

00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:24.330
coming from the community members to believe that you are going to

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:27.260
be able to actually protect them or mitigate the harm that will

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:29.400
come up and that you're going to actually listen to what

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:32.520
their needs are and not try to create a top down environment

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:34.840
of what you think trust and safety looks like.

00:02:34.840 --> 00:02:38.760
So this is how we get down at Black Sky.

00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:42.080
We have volunteer moderators who are community members from the Black

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:43.420
Diaspora internationally.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:46.080
Shout out to JD.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.590
We have an open communication and feedback loop where we have a

00:02:49.690 --> 00:02:52.720
separate signal just for the moderators.

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:55.460
We have a Black Sky trust and safety signal.

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:57.880
And then we have, of course, our all teams.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:01.390
And the style is that if any issues come up or confusion

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:05.030
or there is a difficult case or report that comes through,

00:03:05.030 --> 00:03:07.800
we have full-blown discussions before we decide how to

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.380
moderate that.

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:11.480
And for some people, they may not think that is,

00:03:11.690 --> 00:03:13.380
like, sustainable, but it's worked.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:15.540
And I have the data to prove that later.

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:19.020
And we also have accessible documentation, which was really important to

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:22.000
me as an educator, to make sure that whatever we're

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:25.120
doing internally, you can go on our doc site and you

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:28.100
can read exactly how we're doing it.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.130
And our trust and safety lead, JD, did a really

00:03:30.130 --> 00:03:34.160
good job of creating our internal SOP, which allowed community

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:38.840
members to understand how moderation works as people who may not have

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:40.520
a background in trust and safety.

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:42.980
Because I'm a firm believer that, like, everyone is

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:45.660
an expert on their Black experience and, like, your credentials

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:47.140
honestly don't mean anything, right?

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:49.290
So I have a PhD, but I also have experience with

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:50.560
digital massage noir.

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:52.510
I've also been on the internet since dial-up,

00:03:52.510 --> 00:03:52.960
right?

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:58.510
So my personal experience really shapes how I view safety online.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.470
And it allows you to not let your credentials overrule the

00:04:01.740 --> 00:04:05.080
actual realities of what's happening on the internet, right?

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:07.880
Because the reality is your community doesn't care that you worked

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:10.010
in trust and safety for 15 years if you all don't

00:04:10.010 --> 00:04:12.700
have anything that's actually moderating the harm that they're

00:04:12.770 --> 00:04:14.540
dealing with on a day-to-day basis, right

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:14.760
?

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:18.560
It's a mute point.

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:24.610
So, you know, Black Sky is all about self-

00:04:24.610 --> 00:04:27.560
determination and self-governance, and we really stick

00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:28.320
by that.

00:04:28.340 --> 00:04:30.620
And I know that in a lot of movement spaces, there

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:34.090
are organizations that use these types of buzzwords, but there

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:36.700
still is, like I said earlier, like a top-

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:39.120
down type of effect.

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:40.120
But that's not how it works for us.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.620
So, remember, in the beginning, there were two labels

00:04:43.620 --> 00:04:43.920
.

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:46.340
So when I started moderating, I was really starting to

00:04:46.350 --> 00:04:49.960
think about how there were specific cases that didn't fall under

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:51.120
those two labels.

00:04:51.120 --> 00:04:52.960
And I'll give an example.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.670
There was a report that was made about a particular post,

00:04:55.670 --> 00:04:59.070
and it was actually internalized anti-black rhetoric, right

00:04:59.070 --> 00:04:59.280
?

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:01.250
But the only label we had at the time was anti-

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:02.230
black harassment.

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:03.600
That person was not harassing people.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:06.110
They were making a statement, but it was anti-black

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:06.360
.

00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:08.220
So when I saw that, I was like, ooh,

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:09.870
we actually need more labels.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:12.720
So because we use Black Sky's People's Assembly, which

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:16.380
is through polis, where people can submit features or even

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:19.560
labels or things that they need, I decided to come up

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:23.180
with some labels and I deployed it in the People's Assembly

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:25.120
, and people voted on it, right?

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:28.630
So the community got to decide if these labels were actually important

00:05:28.730 --> 00:05:31.320
, and it was a resounding yes.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:36.030
And we have decided internally that we are going to constantly be

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:40.060
updating our labels because when it comes to trust and safety,

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.960
you have to have your finger on the pulse, right?

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:46.530
You cannot just make a list of trust and safety labels or

00:05:46.630 --> 00:05:49.860
a labeler that only does this one specific thing and not

00:05:49.860 --> 00:05:51.810
think about the cultural context, right?

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:53.780
The times that we're living in, what may come up

00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:56.110
in the news, what new harms may come up that we

00:05:56.110 --> 00:05:58.180
didn't even know was a thing, right?

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:02.120
I'll go over more of the labels that we end up

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:06.920
deploying later, but by having Black Sky's People's Assembly

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:09.500
, it allows us to stay rooted in community, right?

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.450
What I had on my earlier slide, which is the whole

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:16.060
purpose of trying to steward for a group of people.

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:20.260
I know that typically in big tech, it can feel very

00:06:20.260 --> 00:06:25.280
suffocating, not really understanding the transparency of trust and

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:27.800
safety, but I do believe that on the protocol, we

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:32.330
have a responsibility of providing the transparency that people may not get

00:06:32.330 --> 00:06:33.940
on other applications.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:38.060
So, and here's where the data points come in,

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:42.390
this is the researcher in me, this is my favorite part

00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:42.820
.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:45.770
Okay, so when I first became a volunteer moderator, I

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:49.410
think there were maybe like two or three, one of them

00:06:49.410 --> 00:06:51.020
being Rudy.

00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:54.200
And we had a very small team, we still have a

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:58.710
very small team, and we were able to moderate over 49

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.660
,000 reports, right?

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:05.470
Human to human moderation, right, in the trenches.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:09.140
And of those reports, by October 2025, we were able

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:11.650
to label 583 of them as misogynoir.

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:15.270
And like I stated earlier, there is not a moderation tool

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:17.140
on any app that does this.

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:21.940
I want to make that clear every single time.

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:25.340
And the reason why I keep saying this is because as someone

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:29.540
who has literally researched this stuff for so long, experienced it

00:07:29.690 --> 00:07:33.100
, witnessed it, it almost felt as if it was impossible

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:37.250
for it to happen, and this environment made it possible,

00:07:37.250 --> 00:07:41.760
which gives me hope that other moderation tools are possible as well

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.460
for particular groups.

00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:46.010
So the labels that I had submitted to the People's Assembly

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.520
, that the community voted, voted on, and all votes

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:52.300
are anonymous, was anti-black harassment was already one,

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:54.710
misogynoir, but we added violence, right,

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:58.420
because there were people getting threats, and that didn't follow

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:01.100
under harassment or misogynoir.

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:03.340
Doxing, that's an automatic no-no,

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:05.320
that was not a label that we had.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:07.970
We moderated for it, but we also wanted to be

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:09.780
able to label that as well.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:12.690
Non-consensual intimate images, which is important to

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:14.840
me because a lot of the work that I had been doing

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:17.350
before was focusing on, like, deep fake porn and how

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:21.200
people were using AI to manipulate having, you know, non

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:24.360
-consensual sexual relations with people on the internet.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:26.110
Synthetic media, which was a big one, which

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:28.160
is why I talk a lot about, like, changing your

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:31.080
labels and, like, adding new labels is because the up

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:34.090
tick of synthetic media, there needs to be moderation for

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:37.160
that, that is directly impacting the black community.

00:08:37.160 --> 00:08:39.530
So, to be transparent, we've seen things like be

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:45.160
headings, you know, people making videos of Michelle Obama

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:48.640
being, you know, harmed, putting black women's faces

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:50.160
on George Floyd, right?

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:52.390
All of these things are coming through the reports, and if

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:54.760
you're subscribed to our label or use blackside.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:57.220
community, you might not even see those things because when

00:08:57.220 --> 00:08:59.810
we get the reports, we're going through them, right

00:08:59.810 --> 00:08:59.960
?

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:03.590
And then white supremacy or anti-black rhetoric was a very

00:09:03.590 --> 00:09:08.260
interesting conversation amongst the moderators before we decided to, like

00:09:08.260 --> 00:09:11.760
, push these out for votes because we wanted to make sure

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:15.210
that if someone's post got labeled for that, we knew

00:09:15.210 --> 00:09:18.490
how to explain why if they wanted to appeal it, right

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:18.760
?

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:21.470
And when it comes to anti-black rhetoric, when it

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:23.960
comes to misogynoir, these things can also be

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:27.740
internalized as well, and the purpose of the labeler

00:09:27.970 --> 00:09:32.710
and the moderation tool is not to say that one particular race

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:35.690
of people are harming black people, it is that everyone

00:09:35.690 --> 00:09:38.370
can enact in this type of harm, and we have to

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:40.560
moderate towards all of it.

00:09:40.560 --> 00:09:45.560
So, down here, if you know about the labeler

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:46.150
or you use blacksky.

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:48.990
community, which you should be, if someone has a

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:53.320
label on their post, it'll say what the label is

00:09:53.460 --> 00:09:55.360
for, right?

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:57.360
And if they want to appeal it, they can.

00:09:57.360 --> 00:10:00.120
They can click on the label, they can send an email

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:00.760
and appeal it.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:03.450
We have a whole entire appealing process, which also is a

00:10:03.450 --> 00:10:05.560
conversation amongst the team as well.

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:08.510
There are some things that are, like, a no-

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:08.960
go.

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:10.990
If you're doxing non-consensual intimate

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.810
images, like, you're out of here because that's

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.360
just wrong on all levels.

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:17.810
And if we were in the UK, you have 48 hours

00:10:17.810 --> 00:10:19.160
to take it down by law.

00:10:19.160 --> 00:10:21.260
We don't have that here right now, so we have

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:23.160
to, you know, set some boundaries.

00:10:23.160 --> 00:10:27.930
And we also have the option to label accounts that have repeated

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:28.920
behavior.

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:32.280
We have the option to greenlist them, which is a

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:34.720
subscription list where it has all the people who have been green

00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:37.100
listed, which means that it can, like, automatically block

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:37.910
those accounts.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:38.960
You won't see their content.

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:41.910
And then we also have ban from TV as well, which

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:45.760
allows them to not interact with the Black Sky feed.

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:48.710
And this is important because we want to make sure that if

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:52.240
someone is repeatedly causing harm, that we are setting up guard

00:10:52.240 --> 00:10:54.760
rails so they don't continue to cause harm.

00:10:54.760 --> 00:11:00.260
It also requires a lot of cultural nuance, being tapped in

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:03.630
, long conversations, doing your Googles, no Gemini

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:04.520
, right?

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:07.490
It takes a lot of that because there are instances where there

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:09.560
may be a celebrity, I won't say any names,

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.740
who have a history of violence towards Black women, who may

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:16.530
have people rally behind them, but they have a history of

00:11:16.780 --> 00:11:19.360
harassing Black women on different platforms.

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:22.170
They've been banned from those platforms, so we must do

00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:25.490
the same for ours to be proactive, which is something that

00:11:25.490 --> 00:11:27.310
I'm going to also talk about as well.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:30.710
Before I do that, I do want to shout out AC

00:11:30.710 --> 00:11:31.360
ORN.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:37.360
So our wonderful engineer, Richie, made ACORN

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:37.360
.

00:11:37.360 --> 00:11:40.310
And ACORN came out of a lot of the frust

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:43.560
rations we were having with Ozone, to be transparent,

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:46.070
when it came to just accessibility as far as, like,

00:11:46.180 --> 00:11:48.930
being able to do it on a tablet or a mobile phone

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:53.830
, just having certain things that would just make the process easier

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:54.160
.

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:58.150
And although I am not an expert on the back end of

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:01.560
content moderation, that's what JD is really good at,

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:04.760
we were able to actually collaborate on what that would look like

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:07.890
, and they were able to work in tandem to create a

00:12:07.970 --> 00:12:10.910
platform for Black Sky to moderate with.

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:14.780
Another thing is that one of the things that I implemented when

00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:18.760
I first started moderating was ways to take care of yourself

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:18.960
.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:21.270
So I, like, made a little, like, doc

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:24.330
with, like, somatic stuff, like, you know

00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:27.940
, healing and sounds and, like, websites and resources that

00:12:27.940 --> 00:12:29.160
are pinned in the signal.

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:32.640
And we want to continue to build out those types of wellness

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:37.160
things within our setup because content moderation can cause a lot of

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:38.160
decision fatigue.

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:39.360
It can cause a lot of fatigue.

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:40.360
It can cause a lot of trauma.

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:42.580
You see a lot of things that you may not see on

00:12:42.580 --> 00:12:44.360
a day-to-day basis.

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:47.310
And because we have community members doing the moderation and not,

00:12:47.570 --> 00:12:51.540
like, professional trust and safety people, we want to make

00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:55.880
sure that they feel safe as well, especially because commercial content

00:12:55.880 --> 00:13:01.200
moderation is treated like slave labor labor in other countries like the

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:03.560
Philippines, and we don't go for that.

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:09.220
So ACORN was built for Black Sky for us to

00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:15.550
be able to create a more accessible and a space for moderation

00:13:15.600 --> 00:13:16.540
to happen.

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:20.270
And they're continuously building out new features as we see,

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:21.760
like, okay, well, maybe we should do this.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:24.300
Well, maybe we should add this and, like, making

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:25.760
things time-bound as well.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:29.980
So people are forced to take breaks because we had a really

00:13:30.060 --> 00:13:30.760
big backlog.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:33.080
And JD and I were, like, really, like,

00:13:33.190 --> 00:13:36.190
around the clock moderating and, like, Rudy was jumping

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:36.360
in.

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:38.160
And we kind of all realized that, like, okay,

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:41.060
we don't want the other moderators to ever have to

00:13:41.060 --> 00:13:46.560
do that because that can be very traumatic in the long run

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:46.560
.

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:48.940
And we want them to be able to sustain doing the work

00:13:48.980 --> 00:13:50.560
to keep their community safe.

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:55.810
And here on my left is what it looks like when you

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:57.550
go to label.

00:13:57.560 --> 00:14:00.510
So on our side panel, which you all don't see

00:14:00.760 --> 00:14:02.560
, it has all of the labels in their definitions.

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:05.960
So you automatically know what the label is actually about.

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.850
So you don't have to keep going back and forth to

00:14:07.850 --> 00:14:08.360
the SOP.

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:11.050
And then we really encourage all moderators to leave some type

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:11.760
of comment.

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:13.520
I just put massage and wash so you can see where it

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:13.760
goes.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.960
Because if another moderator comes in behind it, they can kind

00:14:16.990 --> 00:14:19.280
of know, like, why this person was moderated this

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:19.760
way.

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:21.360
Is this person a repeat offender?

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:22.760
What do we want to do next?

00:14:22.760 --> 00:14:25.720
And this also helps with appeals, right, because anybody can

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:26.760
repeal the label.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:31.440
And when we have that information in ACORN, it

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:35.160
allows us to be able to make a decision with the investigation

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:37.760
on if it's something that we will, you know,

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:37.760
lift.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:40.560
Or if there's a conversation that needs to be had.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.730
Which I think is really why we have gained a lot of

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:45.590
trust within the community is how we handle these types of situations

00:14:45.590 --> 00:14:45.760
.

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:48.710
So this is where things go wrong in trust and safety.

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:52.580
And I know people have in their bios, like, this

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:55.160
is not a representation of my organization, but it is.

00:14:55.160 --> 00:14:58.110
This is truly how we feel, right?

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:00.560
There is a lack of community trust, right?

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:04.200
People do not trust a lot of people in trust and safety

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:07.550
because there is an ignorance of cultural nuances, right?

00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:10.510
There is an unwillingness to acknowledge mistakes.

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:13.510
A lot of people are reactive instead of proactive.

00:15:13.560 --> 00:15:16.510
And the words and actions don't match.

00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:18.960
And that's a danger zone, right?

00:15:18.960 --> 00:15:19.960
That is a recipe for disaster.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:22.910
And we've all seen disasters everywhere online.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:26.770
And the biggest thing is that not understanding the community you serve

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:27.960
, right?

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:30.920
It is very difficult for your community to trust that you care

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:34.410
about what is important to them if they don't even think

00:15:34.410 --> 00:15:36.960
that you actually know what's going on, right?

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:39.230
That you're so disconnected that, like, oh, I

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:41.550
'm just logging in to do some trust and safety, but

00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:44.310
I don't even pay attention to what's happening in those

00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:45.360
communities.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:48.550
Which is why I really enjoy my role, because not only

00:15:48.590 --> 00:15:50.920
do I get to assist with the content moderation and trust and

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:52.850
safety, but I also get to pay attention to what's

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.160
actually happening within the community.

00:15:55.160 --> 00:15:58.110
And not just within Black Sky, but the protocol at large

00:15:58.380 --> 00:15:58.560
.

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:01.360
And that helps me signal to JD and the other moderators

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:03.360
, like, hey, this topic has come up.

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.360
We may get a lot of reports for this, right?

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:07.870
That's being proactive.

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:10.360
So, you know, I'm not here to, you

00:16:10.390 --> 00:16:14.960
know, bash people over the head, right?

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:17.910
I'm also here to provide repair and to help people rebuild

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:20.560
, because I do really believe in trust and safety.

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:22.620
And I do think that, you know, there is a

00:16:22.930 --> 00:16:27.860
level of grace, but there's also, there is a

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:32.070
level of wanting to do better and to use your self-

00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:34.890
efficacy, believing that you can do better, that

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:36.550
pushes me to run a strict program.

00:16:36.560 --> 00:16:39.510
So this is where the strict program begins for all the trust

00:16:39.740 --> 00:16:40.560
and safety people.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:43.070
Ongoing training, right?

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:46.960
And you need to have your trainings be specific to the things

00:16:46.960 --> 00:16:50.150
that are coming up within your communities, right?

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:54.560
And the training is really good for, not only for your

00:16:54.560 --> 00:16:58.160
internal team to understand, but also like, okay, this

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.250
keeps coming up when we're reporting something and the mods are

00:17:01.390 --> 00:17:02.160
getting stuck on it.

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:05.100
So we need to create a training on this particular label because

00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:07.430
they may not understand what misogynoir is, right

00:17:07.460 --> 00:17:07.750
?

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:08.760
And that was a big thing.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:10.830
People don't really know what misogynoir is and

00:17:10.830 --> 00:17:12.980
they think there's like misogynoir light and mis

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:13.590
ogynoir 2.

00:17:13.590 --> 00:17:16.760
0, but like it all falls under misogynoir

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:16.760
.

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:18.760
And that's a part of the training, right?

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:19.760
Community feedback, right?

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:22.620
If the community is constantly telling you like, why are you

00:17:22.620 --> 00:17:25.160
constantly suspending these specific accounts?

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:26.160
Why is this happening?

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:27.160
What's going on?

00:17:27.160 --> 00:17:29.560
You all need to be transparent about that.

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:32.080
And there is a strategic way to do that through like your

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:35.150
communications channels and trust and safety reports.

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:37.360
Staying mission aligned, right?

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:40.840
Words plus actions that don't match equals a danger zone,

00:17:40.970 --> 00:17:41.560
right?

00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:44.970
If you say you care about a community, you must stay

00:17:44.970 --> 00:17:45.960
mission aligned.

00:17:45.960 --> 00:17:49.470
And that also means that you may have to do some research

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:49.760
.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.160
You might have to actually listen to those being most harmed.

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:55.640
And you may start to start having hard conversations about how your

00:17:55.770 --> 00:17:59.960
trust and safety is set up, what those policies actually mean

00:17:59.960 --> 00:17:59.960
.

00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:02.510
And if you need to go back to the drawing board and

00:18:02.580 --> 00:18:04.960
come into terms with the fact that you may not be equipped

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:06.340
to do these policies on your own.

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:09.180
You may have to hire people who are a part of those

00:18:09.180 --> 00:18:10.760
communities, right?

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:13.700
Have them as consultants to help you build out some of the

00:18:13.700 --> 00:18:16.520
policies for the groups that you are working with.

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:22.080
So in the end, I just want to say that I

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.390
know that trust and safety is really obvious for a lot of

00:18:25.410 --> 00:18:27.560
people because it's very vague.

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:30.520
It's been vague from a user standpoint, from a community

00:18:30.780 --> 00:18:33.560
standpoint, it's vague for researchers like myself.

00:18:33.560 --> 00:18:36.510
But I do believe that from the work that I've been

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:39.590
able to do with Black Sky, from how I see the

00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:43.200
reactions of how we're moderating, from the way we

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:47.700
're able to continue to build and grow and create a community

00:18:47.780 --> 00:18:50.880
ecosystem where people are asking like, well, how are y

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:52.040
'all moderating things?

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:54.990
It lets me know that people are interested in being better at

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:57.560
trust and safety, but like I said, it also takes

00:18:57.560 --> 00:19:00.070
self-efficacy and believing that you can actually do

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:03.110
it and holding yourself accountable when you're trying to take the

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:06.480
easy way out or push the blame on someone else.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:07.480
Thank you.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:25.850
Thank you very much.

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:26.460
That was wonderful.

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:28.700
We have some time for questions.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:29.500
I see one.

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:31.610
How would you like people to refer to you as Dr.

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:32.020
K, Dr.

00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:32.460
Coghill?

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:32.890
Dr.

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:33.400
K is fine.

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:33.720
Wonderful.

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:34.960
I'll bring the mic to you.

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:37.920
Hi, Dr.

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:39.380
K.

00:19:39.380 --> 00:19:40.360
Hi, Brian.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.000
I just want to ask something that you talked about that I

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.510
thought was really important was the understanding the communities that you serve

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:47.760
.

00:19:48.500 --> 00:19:50.870
And one of the things, you know, we've heard

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:53.730
these sayings, which is like, doing trust and safety

00:19:53.730 --> 00:19:55.120
right is impossible.

00:19:55.120 --> 00:19:58.580
And what I think sometimes, what I wonder, what I

00:19:58.580 --> 00:20:04.880
want to ask is, how do you help people define,

00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:11.100
how do we help people understand what the community or communities they

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:12.700
serve are?

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:15.560
So that they're delivering trust and safety, like, for

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:17.710
example, when you think about a blue sky, there's

00:20:17.710 --> 00:20:18.640
not one community.

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:21.390
There's so many communities, and that's why you can

00:20:21.390 --> 00:20:23.180
't moderate them the same way.

00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:26.890
And so how do you, is it that big world social

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:31.740
networks that aren't aligned around an ethos or a mission

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:34.770
are doomed to have this problem?

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:37.080
Or is there a way to do that when you have these

00:20:37.290 --> 00:20:42.010
intersecting groups with different experiences and different backgrounds and different places

00:20:42.180 --> 00:20:42.300
?

00:20:42.380 --> 00:20:45.690
How do you help TNS deal in a space like that

00:20:45.690 --> 00:20:46.040
?

00:20:46.040 --> 00:20:48.990
Yeah, so I want to go back to Dr.

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:51.230
Safiya Noble's book, Algorithms of Oppression

00:20:51.230 --> 00:20:51.440
.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:54.390
I believe in the last chapter she talks about that they need

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:57.200
to bring humanities back into computer science.

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:00.610
They need to hire black women at these trust and safety spaces

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:03.720
and building the algorithms, and that's where it begins,

00:21:03.720 --> 00:21:04.260
right?

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:07.080
A lot of trust and safety teams are overwhelmingly white, and

00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:08.180
that's the problem.

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:11.500
And because of that, it makes it difficult to know what

00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:16.140
the intersecting identities and communities are because you may have some

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:19.480
, like, unchecked biases that you may not even realize

00:21:19.480 --> 00:21:21.240
when you're creating the labels, right?

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:24.400
And you have control over how many labels you have and how

00:21:24.650 --> 00:21:26.080
often you change them.

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:28.960
So if you realize that you're getting complaints or you realize

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:31.140
that there's been an uptick of a particular type

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:34.080
of report, it would make sense to, you know,

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:37.170
laser focus in on that and add that as a label.

00:21:37.260 --> 00:21:40.020
I also think that, like, yes, social networks are

00:21:40.020 --> 00:21:40.220
big.

00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:42.460
There's all types of people, but I also see that

00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:43.410
as an excuse, right?

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:45.800
Because if you want to keep the internet safe, there will

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:47.560
never be a safe internet, but there is a way to

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:48.500
mitigate harm.

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:51.020
And if that is the goal of what you're trying to

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:52.320
do, it is possible.

00:21:52.360 --> 00:21:56.060
It's just going to take the work and also is going

00:21:56.060 --> 00:21:59.750
to require you to be tapped in more so than you may

00:21:59.750 --> 00:22:00.640
not be.

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:05.890
Yeah, and that's why it's important for you to

00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:13.260
have different types of community members and trust and safety people on

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:17.480
your teams so you can have those people with those expert experiences

00:22:17.480 --> 00:22:19.440
, not an expert resume.

00:22:19.440 --> 00:22:27.440
So something that I noticed listening to this talk is

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:35.990
that there feels like there's room being made for restor

00:22:35.990 --> 00:22:41.100
ative justice in communities as part of moderation.

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:45.140
And are there any conversations that you can share about what that

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:47.220
might look like at Black Sky?

00:22:48.860 --> 00:22:51.810
Yeah, so we haven't talked deeply particularly about restorative

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:55.290
justice, but that is a framework that is grounded in the

00:22:55.410 --> 00:22:56.300
work that I do.

00:22:56.360 --> 00:22:59.850
And one of the ways that I think we implement restorative

00:22:59.850 --> 00:23:03.930
justice is through our self-governance and also through our

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:10.420
appeal process, where we will have the conversation about exactly what

00:23:10.420 --> 00:23:13.080
was said, what was done.

00:23:13.080 --> 00:23:16.030
And I know that that can be difficult depending on the scale

00:23:16.250 --> 00:23:18.840
of the organization or the company you're with.

00:23:18.860 --> 00:23:21.610
But that one-to-one is really helpful to explain

00:23:21.610 --> 00:23:25.010
to people, you know, why certain labels were applied.

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:29.480
I also think that because we have such a strong trusting community

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:32.740
, like they trust in us to mitigate the harm, we

00:23:32.740 --> 00:23:37.790
lean into the restorative justice model naturally when it comes to

00:23:37.790 --> 00:23:40.500
how we deal with harm in general.

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:42.880
It's not very punitive, right?

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:45.830
You don't automatically get labeled, you don't automatically get

00:23:46.100 --> 00:23:46.360
banned.

00:23:46.440 --> 00:23:50.170
It is a longer process and there's always room for you

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:53.820
to appeal or for you to want to have a conversation of

00:23:53.820 --> 00:23:55.720
trying to change that behavior.

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:59.230
Because the goal is not to exclude people from community if they

00:23:59.330 --> 00:24:02.390
actually want to come together and do the work to be better

00:24:02.390 --> 00:24:04.160
, you know, community members.

00:24:14.400 --> 00:24:17.910
When trust and safety work goes well, it's often invisible

00:24:18.010 --> 00:24:18.760
, right?

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:20.980
If there's not bad content, it's not out there

00:24:21.170 --> 00:24:21.240
.

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:24.160
And kind of the value to the community maybe isn't felt

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:26.900
or what kinds of work is being done doesn't get seen

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:27.200
.

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:30.080
So transparency reports can be a way to do that, but

00:24:30.080 --> 00:24:32.960
they can be very kind of like pie graph, some numbers

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:34.600
, a little abstract.

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:36.850
Do you have any thoughts on kind of like how to communicate

00:24:37.010 --> 00:24:38.980
with the community, like the work that's being done or

00:24:38.980 --> 00:24:41.150
like, you know, involving people in the process can be

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:41.700
part of that.

00:24:41.780 --> 00:24:45.740
Yeah, so one of the things that I think we do

00:24:45.740 --> 00:24:49.340
well is we do a lot of like blog posts and we

00:24:49.480 --> 00:24:52.600
do a lot of educational stuff.

00:24:52.600 --> 00:24:54.890
That's like one of the big parts of like my work

00:24:55.010 --> 00:24:59.320
in particular is providing like educational materials exactly about why we moderate

00:24:59.320 --> 00:25:02.830
a certain way, how many reports we're getting, really

00:25:02.830 --> 00:25:07.020
like talking about like the, like, which is important for

00:25:07.020 --> 00:25:09.860
a lot of the community members is like when you go to

00:25:09.980 --> 00:25:14.650
moderate something, what is the best way to explain what you

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:16.900
're, what, when you're going to report something,

00:25:16.900 --> 00:25:18.620
what is the best way to explain what you're reporting,

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:19.020
right?

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:21.770
What are the steps to take to make sure that the proper

00:25:21.770 --> 00:25:22.980
label is being put?

00:25:22.980 --> 00:25:27.140
And then also we do not make large decisions around moderation without

00:25:27.140 --> 00:25:29.130
going to the community first.

00:25:29.140 --> 00:25:31.170
And if you've been paying attention to the work we've

00:25:31.170 --> 00:25:33.780
been doing recently with Black Sky Only posts, like we're

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:37.160
not going to move the needle if the community is like,

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:38.660
please give us a moment.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:39.800
We need to think this through.

00:25:39.800 --> 00:25:43.590
And I think that that types of transparency makes it more accessible

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:44.250
as well.

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:45.160
Cause I definitely agree.

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:47.700
Like the pie charts and things can be very confusing.

00:25:47.700 --> 00:25:51.520
So having other mediums of that knowledge base is helpful for

00:25:51.590 --> 00:25:53.740
all different types of community members.

00:25:53.740 --> 00:25:57.210
I had a question.

00:25:57.940 --> 00:26:02.160
You talked earlier about, um, making intentional choices and how

00:26:02.240 --> 00:26:05.080
you moderate and how context is important.

00:26:05.080 --> 00:26:08.790
Um, how do you balance the sense of urgency of moderation

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:13.520
versus, uh, um, collective choice or, or maybe

00:26:13.630 --> 00:26:15.960
, uh, collective choice isn't the best word, but

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:18.140
, uh, seeking, seeking, seeking the choice of other

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:20.610
peers in this trust and safety space to, to make a

00:26:20.610 --> 00:26:22.240
choice together about something.

00:26:22.240 --> 00:26:26.140
Uh, cause I, I just wonder about how difficult it

00:26:26.140 --> 00:26:28.800
is to be, uh, how, how important it is

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:31.360
to be immediately reactive versus more intentional.

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:36.000
Yeah, so because we have, um, very detailed labels

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.230
and our SFP is labeled, when we do get edge

00:26:39.230 --> 00:26:41.300
cases, they're very rare.

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:44.050
So the way that we do it is like, we go

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:47.300
to, yeah, we go to our chat and somebody will

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:51.120
drop it in and ask for feedback and people will chime in

00:26:51.120 --> 00:26:54.200
on the feedback and then we'll move with the decision.

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:57.690
Um, if something urgent comes in nine times out of 10

00:26:57.690 --> 00:27:01.020
, it is something that's already attached to a label,

00:27:01.020 --> 00:27:01.760
right?

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:04.140
Um, edge cases are things that are like when we had

00:27:04.180 --> 00:27:06.510
the anti-black rhetoric thing, we were like, is

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:08.520
that harassment or is that rhetoric?

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:11.420
That is what those conversations look like.

00:27:11.420 --> 00:27:14.370
But if someone is doing something that is violent, there's

00:27:14.610 --> 00:27:16.990
not really a conversation that needs to be had.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.820
It's very like transparent and clear.

00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:26.850
As a person who has these particular intersecting identities and

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:32.360
it's a sort of the work that I've thought about

00:27:32.360 --> 00:27:35.000
a lot, how do you deal with things like anti-

00:27:35.090 --> 00:27:36.400
fatness as anti-blackness?

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:39.570
Like, where is that sitting today in the moderation that you

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:40.020
're doing?

00:27:40.180 --> 00:27:42.640
Yeah, so we are constantly working on new labels and that

00:27:42.640 --> 00:27:43.690
is one of the labels.

00:27:43.720 --> 00:27:46.010
But right now, like, just like when we were using

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:48.280
just misogynoir and anti-black harassment, if

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:49.870
you're being fat phobic to a black person, that

00:27:49.970 --> 00:27:50.870
's anti-black rhetoric.

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:52.620
Yeah.

00:27:52.620 --> 00:27:53.760
Yeah.

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:56.720
But we are going to be adding more specific labels like text

00:27:56.990 --> 00:27:59.920
urism, colorism, Islamophobia, all those particular

00:28:00.310 --> 00:28:00.880
things.

00:28:03.740 --> 00:28:04.510
Hi, Dr.

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:04.900
K.

00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:08.990
Just trying to empathize with or trying to put myself in

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:13.370
the place of your team, how are you distributing the workload

00:28:13.370 --> 00:28:16.200
of moderating in a way that's equitable?

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:20.320
And you mentioned some things are time-bound.

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:21.680
But, yeah.

00:28:21.680 --> 00:28:24.440
So, oh, sorry.

00:28:24.440 --> 00:28:25.200
I got stuff to think.

00:28:25.200 --> 00:28:30.700
So, our volunteer moderators are not required to moderate,

00:28:30.700 --> 00:28:36.580
which means that a lot of the maybe access moderation does fall

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:38.800
on, like, JD and I.

00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:42.300
Mainly JD at this point, but we are bringing on new

00:28:42.300 --> 00:28:46.940
volunteer moderators and we are looking into possibly building out a

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:48.700
peer-to-peer moderation.

00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:52.860
So, we are able to distribute it more evenly.

00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:56.370
But because it's volunteer moderation, we do not require anyone

00:28:56.470 --> 00:28:57.300
to moderate.

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.720
Like, they can jump in and out whenever they want because

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:01.950
that's what, like, safety looks like in that space

00:29:01.950 --> 00:29:02.140
.

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:05.400
Well, we've got just a few moments left, so

00:29:05.400 --> 00:29:06.910
let's do one more thank you for Dr.

00:29:06.910 --> 00:29:07.250
K.

00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:10.660
Thank you.
